<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>veeshanMurtak</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Mystic<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jan 2004<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><b>Part 1 - Versatility vs Power</b><br />
<br />
One of the shaman's biggest strengths is supposed to be his versatility. We have a great number of abilities we can use. Most other classes have far fewer options. The questions is, "How versatile does one have to be to make up for lost power?" or conversely, "How powerful do my extra options have to be for my versatility to be useful?".<br />
<br />
There are a few different types of abilities - some abiltities you either have or have not. Spells like Levitation or Ressurection or abilities like Invisibility fall into this category.<br />
Other abilities are innate, like tanking ability or a necromancer's mana regeneration.<br />
And yet other abilities are mutually exclusive, meaning using one of them makes using other such abilities impossible. Healing, doing damage and shaman mana regenration fall into this category.<br />
<br />
The first category is pretty easy to evaluate - any extra ability will be just as useful to a class as the first ability.<br />
<br />
The second category is similar, though additionally these abilities have a degree to their usefulness, like warriors tanking better then knights. However extra abilities are still as useful as the first ability and a more powerful ability is more useful.<br />
<br />
The third category is radically different. Adding new such abilities to a class will provide more options but every such ability after the first is less useful then the previous. In game terms, being able to heal is very good. Being able to heal and nuke is a decent bit better. Being able to heal and nuke and mez is a tiny amount better. Being able to heal and nuke and mez and stun is still better but by such a small amount as to not matter.<br />
<br />
Thus a class that can nuke for x amount and heal for y amount is (all other abilities being equal) strictly worse then then a class that can nuke for 2x or a class that can heal for 2y. Basically, for versitility to be useful any exclusive abilities have to be quite close to the benchmark (usually the best ability).<br />
Let me show a few (simplified) examples:<br />
- A cleric's CH heals for 7500, a druid's for 4680 and a shaman's for 1950. It is generally agreed that a druid CH is acceptable as a substitution for a cleric CH in most situations. Thus the druid's versatility is useful in this case. A shaman CH however is nowhere close to the cleric CH and thus, while not useless per se, is not worth losing other abilities for.<br />
- A shaman's best strength buff is Ferine Avatar at 140 strength. A ranger's strength buff adds 35 strength. Even though this is not an exclusive ability, the ranger buff is so far behind the shaman buff that it's loss would hardly be noticed.<br />
<br />
The above examples are of course oversimplified in the extreme. They do however illustrate one of my main points:<br />
An exclusive ability should be within 30% of the top ability in question to be a viable alternative. A nonexclusive ability should be within 50% of the top ability in question to be a viable alternative. Else the ability will be better left to others.<br />
<br />
In game terms:<br />
Druids can in many situations act as a main healer instead of a cleric (main healer being defined as having a large CH-type spell within 30% of a cleric's).<br />
<br />
Shaman are not able to do this in a large part of the content (because their CH-type spell is not in this range).<br />
<br />
Paladin buffs are an acceptable substitute for cleric buffs as the stats are within 50% of cleric buffs.<br />
<br />
That being clarified let me explain a few key problems of the shaman class.<br />
<br />
A shaman is to a certain extent a jack of all trades. Shaman have a large variety of spells for a lot of situations. Many of these spells used to be pretty close to the best spells in their category. Expansion by expansion many of these spells have been scaled back compared to other classes' spells until today shaman spells are often the worst in their category.<br />
All the versatility in the world is useless when all the options are third class or worth in their category.<br />
<br />
- Shaman HP buffs are the weakest of any class (tied with rangers).<br />
- Shaman healing is tied for third place with paladins (only beastlords and rangers heal worse) and is solidly past the 30% difference from cleric healing to be considered a viable alternative.<br />
- Shaman nuking is the weakest of all casters.<br />
- Shaman DoTs are solidly behind necromancer DoTs and (due to resist modifiers) behind druid DoTs.<br />
<br />
That leaves a shaman with stat buffing, slowing and haste as tier 1 / 2 abilties.<br />
- Stat buffs are largely useless due to caps.<br />
- A very large part of this (and the last 2) expansion mitigates slow. Even a minor slow mitigation easily halves the effectiveness of slow.<br />
- Haste is still pretty useful.<br />
<br />
This is part one of the shaman problem. There is two things shaman do really well - buff stats and slow, both of which is getting more useless every expansion.<br />
As an example for versatility done right consider the bard. A bard is among the best at<br />
- hasting (first)<br />
- mana regeneration (first)<br />
- crowd control (close second)<br />
- pulling (first)<br />
- resist buffs (first)<br />
- damage shields (first)<br />
- slows (4th but within 30% of the top slower)<br />
This is why bards are a great class. They are actually good at what they can do.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
