	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><b>Part 3 - Mana regeneration for everyone</b><br />
<br />
Mana regeneration is supposedly the area where shaman excel and we do have the biggest potential mana regeneration. The ratio of shaman to non-shaman mana regeneration has shifted a lot though.<br />
Every casting class now has some mana regeneration buff now, many of them castable on others and many of them stacking. Flowing thought gear is easy to get nowadays. Horses add a large amount of mana regeneration.<br />
<br />
Now, all of these are usable by shaman too. But every time a fixed amount of mana regeneration is added to everyone the shaman suffers. We were balanced to regenerate not a fixed amount more mana then other classes but to regen a multiple of it, and this multiple is shrinking with every expansion since Kunark.<br />
<br />
At the same time this ontributes to problem two - the more mana everyone regenerates the more a shaman is expected to do, further reducing the time to cannibalize and thus reducing the advantage in mana regeneration even further.<br />
<br />
This is part three of the shaman problem. Our mana regeneration, while impressive on paper, is not nearly enough to sustain our ineffective, inefficient, slow spells to a degree where we can pull our weight in groups. This is getting worse every time more flowing thought gear enters the world, every time bigger mana regeneration buffs are created and every time another horse is bought.<br />
<br />
_____________________<br />
<b>numbers for the above</b><br />
This is a comparison of the mana regeneration available during Kunark and today. It is listed in mana per tick. The last column shows the upgrade percentage. The figures for magicians, shaman and necromancers do not account for damage taken  and the magician figures do not account for the mana cost of generating mod rods. This is mainly a comparison of the various upgrades the classes received, and thus the results should still be valid.<blockquote><pre>Code:<hr />
Shaman       72 self                     89 self                 +  24%
Enchanter    11 self   11 group          18 self   18 group      +  64%
Necromancer  31 self                     50 self   30 group      +  61%
Bard                   14 group                    21 group      +  50%
Druid         3 self                     12 self    8 group      + 300%
<hr /></pre></blockquote><i>(Magicians are not listed in this table as the recast time of their mod rod was added later.)</i><br />
<br />
These classes had the following mana regeneration abilities added since Kunark<blockquote><pre>Code:<hr />
Shadowknight           10 group
Beastlord     9 self    9 group
Wizard        8 self
Cleric        8 self
Paladin       3 self
Ranger        3 self
Magician                9 group
<hr /></pre></blockquote>As you can easily see shaman have received the least upgrade to their mana regeneration (in addition to profiting less from flowing thought and other classes' buffs then all other classes).<br />
<br />
Mana regeneration used to be precious, an ability few classes had in any form. Today literally every class that can cast spells has a form of mana regeneration.</p>
	
	
	
	
