	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><b>Part 5 - Raid stacking</b><br />
<br />
Some spells, noticeably buffs, change their value on raids - for example noone is going to use a ranger's natureskin as it will be overwritten by the better druid spell. These are the spells a shaman might use on raids:<br />
- Focus<br />
- stat buffs<br />
- Slow<br />
- Malos<br />
- Malosinia<br />
- Nukes (Velium Strike)<br />
- DoTs (Bane / Blood of Saryrn)<br />
- Heals (Tnarg's / Quiescence)<br />
- Ferine Avatar<br />
<br />
Focus + the few needed stat buffs can easily be done by a single shaman. Another major part of this list is debuffing (Malos / Malosinia / slow ). Debuffing does not stack however - you can only slow a given MOB once after all. However due to resists and the spawned adds on today's raids there is usually work for two, sometimes even three shaman.<br />
<br />
DoT usage on raids is tricky - unless there a multiple MOBs to spread the aggro on a shaman will easily pull aggro of even the best equipped tanks when stacking DoTs. Multiple MOBs are generally killed or mezzed though - meaning DoTs are at best used to augment nuke damage.<br />
<br />
So the stacking roles for a shaman on a raid are healing, nuking and casting Ferine Avatar. Shaman nuke damage is the worst of any caster and shaman healing is the weakest of the priests (and arguably worse then a paladin's). Shaman mana regeneration also does not come into play on raids - I can not remember the last time that people actually ran out of mana ona given encounter.<br />
<br />
This is part five of the shaman problem. The stacking abilities of a shaman are the weakest parts of the class. Every shaman after the second will feel like a second rate druid (and be about as useful).</p>
	
	
	
	
		<div class="smallfont"><i>Last edited by veeshanMurtak on 03-07-2004 at <span class="time">11:45 AM</span>. </i></div>
	
	
